Description: Cypriot terracotta figure of goddess with uplifted arms and headdress. Handmade in primitive style. Head only with broken headdress. Pale buff fabric with abundant dark grey, white and red inclusions.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Temple of Aphrodite (Naukratis), Context Φ16 or 17
Curator's comments: Though many close parallels exist (particularly the flat-chested types from Yeroskipou-Monagri Karageorghis 1998, 15-17, pls 8.7-11 Types I(i)77-80), the goddess with uplifted arms type continued from the ‘11th down to the early 5th centuries BC, with very few changes’ (ibid. 17). This example is most likely from the Cypro-Archaic period as it was found in a ‘26th Dynasty context’ along with British Museum EA1911,0710.92-106 (Bailey 2008, 186), marked "T ΑΦ16" or "T ΑΦ17" (Temple of Aphrodite context 16 or 17). See also AES 50121 from the British Museum. Karageorghis, V. 1998. The coroplastic art of ancient Cyprus. VI. The Cypro-Archaic period small female figurines. Nicosia, University of Cyprus.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (DA.002) (Phase 1)
